11.body: State cannot be modified after it is created. String Warning List is not actually immutable. Rather, it is compile-time read-only. You can cast a List into a MutableList and change the underlying data üò±. Example how we can change the data in a List: val list = listOf(1,2,3) println(list) (list as MutableList<Int>)[2] = 999 println(list) For more immutable support, use Google's Guava or JetBrain's Kotlinx Immutable Collections Library.

When you need to initialise and compute to derive at one goal When you don't need an object but only use it to compute something class Person { var age = 0 fun futureAge(years: Int) = age + years
}
val person = Person() person.age = 50
person.doThis()
person.thenThat()
val ageInTenDecades = futureAge(100) val ageInTenDecades = person.run { age = 50 doThis() thenThat() getFinalFutureAge(100)
}

43.body: Data class is like a class but implements for you: equals() and hashCode() toString() copy() Data class is the idiomatic way to define objects that contains only data. A common operation you would perform on data is comparison - this is where the equals function comes in handy. Note that data classes, however, do not translate to Java's Records. You need the @JvmRecord annotation.
